        "excerpt": "Why do you quarrel with me? Why do you test the LORD?",
        "body": "The episode at Rephidim is the fourth major complaint in the wilderness narrative (cf. 14:11-12; 15:24; 16:2-3), and it is the most theologically named. What distinguishes Massah and Meribah from the earlier complaints is Moses's own diagnosis in verse 2: the quarrel with him is simultaneously a testing of the LORD. The people are not asking a geographical question — they are issuing a theological ultimatum. The demand 'give us water that we may drink' (17:2) carries the subtext of 17:7: 'Is the LORD among us, or not?' Presence is being subjected to a performance test. God must produce on demand or be deemed absent.\n\nThis is the theological center of the episode, and it is the diagnosis that Psalm 95 and Hebrews 3-4 lift into canonical warning. Psalm 95:8-9 reads: 'Do not harden your hearts as at Meribah, as in the day of Massah in the wilderness, where your fathers tested Me; they tried Me, though they had seen My work.' The sin was not ignorance. Israel had seen the plagues, the parted sea, the bitter water made sweet (15:25), and the manna from heaven (ch. 16). They tested God with full knowledge of His track record. Hebrews 3:7-11 applies this to any generation that hears God's voice and refuses to trust it — the Massah-Meribah pattern is the anatomy of the hardened heart in every epoch.\n\nMoses's own response models the alternative. He does not defend himself, does not answer the accusation of intentional homicide (17:3), and does not retaliate. He brings the unfiltered complaint to God: 'What shall I do with this people? A little more and they will stone me' (17:4). This is transparent intercession — he names both the people's sin and his own fear without editing either. The mediator's access to God is the community's only resource when they have exhausted their own.\n\nGod's response is immediate and disarming. He does not rebuke Israel first. He provides: 'Pass before the people... I will stand before you there on the rock' (17:5-6). The provision precedes the verdict. The place-names Massah and Meribah (17:7) are assigned after the water is flowing, which means Israel names its failure only after God has already answered it. This is the character of the God they were accusing of absence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasah* (to test, 17:2, 7) is the same verb used when God tests Abraham in Genesis 22:1 — same word, reversed subjects. When God tests, it is to strengthen and reveal; when Israel tests God, it is to demand proof as a precondition of trust. *Riv* (to quarrel, 17:2, 7) is legal contention — a lawsuit against the covenant Lord. The place-names *Massah* ('testing') and *Meribah* ('quarreling') literalize the verbs into geography, so every future traveler who passes that campsite reads Israel's theology lesson in the landscape."
