        "title": "The rock at Horeb — divine presence as the source of provision",
        "range": "17:5-6",
        "excerpt": "Behold, I will stand before you there on the rock at Horeb; and you shall strike the rock, and water will come out of it.",
        "body": "The command in 17:5-6 is theologically dense in three specific ways. First, God positions Himself on the rock *before* Moses arrives. The phrase 'I will stand before you there' is anticipatory — God is already at the place of need before the mediator reaches it. The provider is not responding to the need; He is awaiting the servant who comes in obedience. This is the posture of the One who in John 4:10 offers living water to a woman who came only for the kind she could draw herself.\n\nSecond, the rock is at Horeb — the mountain of God's covenantal self-disclosure (Exodus 3:1; 19:1ff). The water does not come from a random geological feature; it comes from the seat of divine revelation. Provision and presence are inseparable in the theology of Exodus. Later rabbinic tradition developed this into the legend of a traveling rock that accompanied Israel (attested in Pseudo-Philo and various Targumim), and Paul in 1 Corinthians 10:4 engages that tradition while correcting it typologically: 'they drank from a spiritual rock that followed them, and the rock was Christ.' Paul's reading does not allegorize the event into non-history — it identifies the pre-incarnate Lord as the one whose presence made the provision possible. The rock that stood at Horeb and yielded water under the blow of Moses's staff is the same One who, struck on the cross, pours out living water to all who are thirsty (John 7:37-38).\n\nThird, the staff Moses carries is explicitly identified as 'the staff with which you struck the Nile' (17:5). This is the same instrument through which God brought the ten plagues on Egypt. Its reappearance here signals continuity: the God who judged Egypt's gods is the same God who now provides for His people. The instrument of judgment becomes the instrument of provision — the same theological movement the New Testament makes with the cross.\n\nThe elders of Israel function as witnesses (17:6). Moses does not perform this miracle in private or in a narrowly prophetic context — the representative leadership of the nation sees it. This has legal force: the event is established by multiple witnesses and cannot later be described as Moses's private experience.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsur* (rock) is used in the Psalms as a divine title: 'The LORD is my rock and my fortress' (Psalm 18:2); 'the Rock of Israel' (Psalm 78:35). The choice of *tsur* in 17:6 rather than a generic stone word (*even*) may already carry this resonance. The verb *nakhah* (to strike) is the same root used of the plagues (Exodus 7:25; 8:16; 9:15, 25) — the verbal link between judgment on Egypt and provision for Israel is not accidental."
